@flexiarg measurement/warrant-travels-with-the-number
@title A Number Without Its Warrant Is an Assertion — Make Disputes Checkable
@sigils [⚖/🔗]
@keywords warrant, velocity, metric, provenance, dispute, escalation, checkable, evidence, derivation basis
@audience anyone publishing a computed metric that someone may later dispute
@tone procedural
@style pattern

! conclusion: Every computed number that feeds a decision (a velocity, a score, a rate) must carry its WARRANT — the basis, rule, and inputs it was derived from — in the record itself, so a later dispute is settled by checking, not by remembering. A number whose warrant lives in someone's head is an assertion wearing a measurement's clothes.

  + context: Metrics get computed, recorded, and consumed by decisions
    (escalations, gates, rankings). The computation's basis is obvious
    to whoever wrote it, on the day they wrote it.

  + IF:
      You record a computed metric that a decision will consume — or
      that a person may later contest.

  + HOWEVER:
      The record carries only the value: the choice of rule, the input
      window, and the exclusions live in code history and heads — so
      when the number is disputed (and load-bearing numbers always
      eventually are), the dispute becomes archaeology or authority
      instead of arithmetic.

  + THEN:
      Attach the warrant to the number where it is stored: the rule
      (or its id/sha), the inputs (or pointers to them), and the
      exclusions/assumptions. The test: a skeptical reader can
      recompute the number from the record alone, or point at exactly
      which warranted step they reject.

  + BECAUSE:
      Checkable disputes converge; unchecked ones escalate. A warrant
      makes the number falsifiable at the step grain — which is what
      separates evidence from assertion (kin: the evidence-over-
      assertion discipline; [[measurement/error-needs-structure-to-teach]]
      is this pattern applied to error records specifically).

  + canonical-instance:
      M-first-flights (futon3c): the cycle-5 escalation dispute — the
      mission requires "the warrant for each velocity recorded so the
      cycle-5 escalation dispute is checkable"; velocity records carry
      typed targets ({:type :address-sorry, :target "sorry/..."}) and
      the WANT is that every such number can be re-derived from its
      stored basis by a stranger.
